{{short description|Shinto kami}} {{Expand Japanese}} {{Infobox deity | type = Shinto | name = Toshigami | deity_of = Harvest, grain | member_of = | image = Toshigami (Otoshi-no-kami).png | alt = | caption = | other_names = Toshigami (大年神) | hiero = | avatar_birth = | avatar_end = | script_name = 年神 or 歳神 | script = [[Japanese language|Japanese]] | consorts = {{ubl| {{nihongo|Ino-hime|伊怒比売|}} | {{nihongo|Kaguyo-hime|香用比売|}} | {{nihongo|Amechikarumizu-hime|天知迦流美豆比売|}} }} | father = [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto|Susanoo]] | mother = [[Kamuōichi-hime]] | siblings = [[Ukanomitama]] | offspring = [[Oyamakui no Kami]] | region = | festivals = }}
{{nihongo|'''Toshigami'''|年神 or 歳神|Toshigami ''or'' Tomo|lit. "year god"}}, also known as {{nihongo|'''Ōtoshi-no-kami'''|大年神||lit. "great year god"}}, is a [[Japanese mythology|Japanese]] [[kami]] and a part of the [[Shinto]] [[Pantheon (religion)|pantheon]].
==Etymology== The 年 (nen) kanji originally meant "harvest", which became "year" over time as harvest happened once each year. ''Toshigami'' was therefore the god of abundant harvests, and specifically of grain or rice.<ref name="shinmei kokugakuin"/><ref name="kotobank"/> The character 神 (kami) literally means "god" or "deity".
==Mythology== ===Parentage and siblings=== According to the ''[[Kojiki]]'', Toshigami was the son of [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto|Susanoo]] and [[Kamuo Ichihime]] and the older brother of [[Ukanomitama]].<ref name="shinmei kokugakuin"/><ref name="kotobank"/>
===Family=== Toshigami had offspring through three different wives: {{nihongo|Ino-hime|伊怒比売|}}, {{nihongo|Kaguyo-hime|香用比売|}}, and {{nihongo|Amechikarumizu-hime|天知迦流美豆比売|}}.<ref name="shinmei kokugakuin"/> Through Ino-hime, his children include {{nihongo|Ohokuni-mitama|大国御魂神|}}, {{nihongo|Kara-kami|韓神|}},<ref name="ynu kuniyasu 198910"/> {{nihongo|Sofuri-kami|曾富理神|}}, {{nihongo|Shirahi-no-kami|白日神|}}, and {{nihongo|Hijiri-no-kami|聖神|}}. His children by Kaguyo-hime include {{nihongo|Ōkaguyama-tomi|大香山戸臣神|}} and {{nihongo|Mitoshi-no-kami|御年神|}}. With Amechikarumizu-hime, he had {{nihongo|Okitsu-hiko-no-kami|奥津日子神|}}, {{nihongo|Okitsu-hime-no-mikoto|奥津比売命|}}, {{nihongo|[[Oyamakui no Kami|Oyamakui-no-kami]]|大山咋神|}},<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-08-17 |title=Ōtoshi {{!}} 國學院大學デジタルミュージアム |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9164 |access-date=2023-11-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220817071922/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9164 |archive-date=2022-08-17 }}</ref> {{nihongo|Niwa-tsuhi-no-kami|庭津日神|}}, {{ill|Ikasuri Shrine|lt=Asuha-no-kami|ja|阿須波神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ikasuri Shrine|lt=Hahiki-no-kami|ja|波比岐神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{nihongo|Kaguyama-tomi-no-kami|香山戸臣神|}}, {{nihongo|Hayamato-no-kami|羽山戸神|}}, {{nihongo|Niwataka-tsuhi-no-kami|庭高津日神|}}, and {{nihongo|Ōtsuchi-no-kami|大土神|}}. ==Family tree== {{Eight generations of Izumo}}
